      <hedline>
        <hl1>Don't Go for the Gold</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Joan G Haahr, letter, responds to Patricia Nelson Limerick's May 7 comparison of Internet-business boom to California Gold Rush (M)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Two further analogies to Patricia Nelson Limerick's comparison of the Internet-business boom to the Gold Rush (''Of Forty-Niners, Oilmen and the Dot-Com Boom,'' May 7):</p>
        <p>* The people who struck it rich were those who got in early and found the large nuggets. Late-comers got only small amounts of dust.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Two further analogies to Patricia Nelson Limerick's comparison of the Internet-business boom to the Gold Rush (''Of Forty-Niners, Oilmen and the Dot-Com Boom,'' May 7):</p>
        <p>* The people who struck it rich were those who got in early and found the large nuggets. Late-comers got only small amounts of dust.</p>
        <p>* The people who benefited most were not the prospectors but those, like Levi Strauss, who outfitted and served them. That's a good omen for Cisco Systems, Network Appliance  and other companies, not themselves dot-coms, whose software supplies the Internet.</p>
        <p>JOAN G. HAAHR  The Bronx, May 7</p>
      </block>
